After decades of psychological research, a new method of treatment was developed.

Instead of observing trauma from the outside, therapists learned to enter the patient’s dreams, where memories form without filters.

This is made possible by a device known as the D.I.V.E. Unit (Dream Interface & Visualization Engine).

The machine resembles a sealed box. Once the patient falls asleep, two headphone-like interfaces are connected, one to the patient, and one to the therapist.

When both signals synchronize, the dream opens.

